# Docker & Container Architecture Standards

**Description**: Comprehensive Docker containerization and microservice architecture standards following modern best practices. Essential for all containerized development and deployment.

**Key Focus Areas**: Multi-stage builds, container optimization, service communication, networking, orchestration, development workflows

## Docker Build Standards

### Multi-Stage Builds
- **Always Use Multi-Stage**: Use multi-stage builds for all production containers
- **Build Optimization**: Separate build dependencies from runtime dependencies
- **Layer Caching**: Optimize layer order for maximum caching efficiency
- **Base Image Selection**: Use official, minimal base images (alpine, distroless, scratch when possible)
- **Security Scanning**: Regularly scan images for vulnerabilities

### Container Optimization
- **Minimize Layers**: Combine RUN commands where logical
- **Remove Unnecessary Files**: Clean up package managers and temporary files
- **Use .dockerignore**: Exclude unnecessary files from build context
- **Non-Root Users**: Always run containers as non-root users
- **Resource Limits**: Define appropriate CPU and memory limits

## Service Communication & Networking

### Internal Communication (CRITICAL)
- **Service Names**: Use Docker Compose service names for internal communication
- **Internal Ports**: Always use internal container ports for service-to-service communication
- **Service Discovery**: Rely on Docker's built-in DNS resolution
- **Health Checks**: Implement and use health checks for service readiness

### Network Configuration
- **Custom Networks**: Create custom networks for service isolation
- **Network Segmentation**: Separate frontend, backend, and data networks where appropriate
- **DNS Resolution**: Use service names instead of IP addresses
- **External Network**: Make networks external for cross-compose communication

## Docker Compose Orchestration

### Service Definition Standards
- **Health Checks**: Define health checks for all services
- **Restart Policies**: Use appropriate restart policies (unless-stopped, on-failure)
- **Environment Variables**: Use .env files and environment variable substitution
- **Volumes**: Use named volumes for data persistence
- **Dependencies**: Define service dependencies with depends_on and conditions

### Development vs Production
- **Override Files**: Use docker-compose.override.yml for development-specific settings
- **Environment Separation**: Maintain separate configurations for different environments
- **Secret Management**: Use Docker secrets or external secret management in production

## Container Lifecycle Management

### Health Checks & Monitoring
- **Implement Health Endpoints**: All services must have health check endpoints
- **Define Health Check Commands**: Use HEALTHCHECK instruction in Dockerfiles
- **Monitor Container Status**: Track container health in orchestration

### Graceful Shutdown
- **Signal Handling**: Handle SIGTERM and SIGINT signals properly
- **Connection Cleanup**: Close database and external connections gracefully
- **Request Completion**: Allow in-flight requests to complete before shutdown

### Resource Management
- **Define Limits**: Set CPU and memory limits for all containers
- **Resource Reservations**: Define minimum resource requirements
- **Monitoring**: Monitor resource usage and adjust limits as needed

## Development Environment Setup

### Local Development Standards
- **Development Compose**: Separate docker-compose.dev.yml for development
- **Volume Mounts**: Use bind mounts for source code during development
- **Hot Reloading**: Enable hot reloading for development services
- **Debug Ports**: Expose debug ports only in development environment

### Development Workflow
- **Code Changes**: Make changes to source code
- **Local Testing**: Test changes in containerized environment
- **Integration Testing**: Validate service communication
- **Documentation**: Update relevant documentation
- **Commit**: Commit with conventional commit messages

## Production Deployment Patterns

### Container Registry
- **Image Tagging**: Use semantic versioning for image tags
- **Registry Security**: Use private registries with proper authentication
- **Image Signing**: Sign images for security validation
- **Automated Builds**: Use CI/CD for automated image builds

### Orchestration Platforms
- **Kubernetes Ready**: Design containers to work with Kubernetes
- **Docker Swarm Compatible**: Ensure compatibility with Docker Swarm
- **Environment Agnostic**: Make containers work across different orchestration platforms

### Security Considerations
- **Secrets Management**: Never include secrets in images
- **Network Policies**: Implement network segmentation
- **Image Scanning**: Regularly scan for vulnerabilities
- **Runtime Security**: Implement runtime security monitoring

## Service Architecture Patterns

### Microservices Design
- **Single Responsibility**: Each service should have one clear purpose
- **Data Ownership**: Each service should own its data
- **API Design**: Design consistent, versioned APIs
- **Async Communication**: Use message queues for async operations

### Service Mesh Integration
- **Sidecar Ready**: Design services to work with service mesh sidecars
- **Observability**: Include proper logging and metrics endpoints
- **Circuit Breakers**: Implement resilience patterns
- **Load Balancing**: Design for external load balancing

## Testing Strategies

### Container Testing
- **Unit Tests**: Test application logic in containers
- **Integration Tests**: Test service-to-service communication
- **End-to-End Tests**: Test complete workflows across services
- **Performance Tests**: Validate performance under load

This architecture ensures scalable, maintainable, and secure containerized applications following modern Docker best practices.